<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
 The elemental tanks, the mage nukes for the majority of the damage.<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
This is often not true. In fact, the most mana efficient fighting style for mages generally involves letting the elemental deal most of the damage, while dealing a smaller portion through nukes, although this leads to longer fights.<br>
<br>
What is clear is that the majority of damage dealt by a beastlord is done via the warder.<br>
<br>
I think a variety of circumstances conspire to make the lords themselves weaker than they ought to be, and since warder changes, long overdue, are in their chaotic tuning stage, it is natural that beastlords press as hard as they can now for warder upgrades.<br>
<br>
I think the current pain threshold for many mages is the 54 and 60 water elementals. These are our specialty damage pets, and do not tank well (although probably better than many mages care to admit). If, in the current round of improvements, warders on average do no better than those elementals, then the mage community will not object strongly. This includes factors like positioning, as both warders and water elementals do far and away their best damage from behind.<br>
<br>
Using similar reasoning, since earth elementals are the tanks, you should press for at minimum earth elemental damage independent of positioning. The earth elemental is our tanking pet, but is a better damage dealer than many mages care to admit.<br>
<br>
Between these two limits you would have a significant better warder, something close to what the majority of beastlords aspire too, and because of those two bounds, the argument could be carried to mages <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  (I know I would work actively to calm mages down in that case).</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
This would be a good solid step forward.<br>
<br>
Then, after hell freezes...I mean beastlord melee is fixed, and a more complete picture of beastlord capabilities becomes clear, then if further adjustments need to be made for warders, it can proceed in a more rationale fashion.<br>
<br>
One last comment. Many of you are unsatisfied with the procs, some to the point of wishing to minimize or even abandon them. Do not. While they will make your warders harder to evaluate, procs are important source of magical damage, which is independent of AC. With significant procs, damage can be dealt to high AC targets. The cost is lower damage against magic resistant mobs, but if nearly all your damage output is melee, then you are less flexible.<br>
<br>
Razamatazz Pizzazz<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
